{"questionId":"20380","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Two straight fences meet at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and a field lies between them.</p>\n<p>A horse is tied to a post, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math>, by a rope of length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> metres. Point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math> is on one fence and&nbsp;point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> is on the other, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>PD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>PE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>PA</mtext><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext><mover><mtext>P</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>E</mtext><mo>=</mo><mi>θ</mi></math> radians. This is shown in&nbsp;the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/f1ba8bcdc1e69afbba140214e41b62dca5c09c35.png\"></p>\n<p>The length of the arc <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>DE</mtext></math> shown in the diagram is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>28</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The area of field that the horse can reach is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>460</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>m</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><mfrac><mn>392</mn><msup><mi>θ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>460</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43917</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>44</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"20380","referenceCode":"21M.2.SL.TZ1.8c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The area of field that the horse can reach is 460 m2. Find the value of θ.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—Circle: radians, arcs, sectors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}